      {
        "id": 2190714,
        "name": "Peter Moy",
        "username": "P_Moy",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/p/a9a28c/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2017-05-29T14:44:51.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Bricking throughout with an orange rim.  Fragrant bouquet of spice, truffles, rose petals, damp earth and the slightest hints of red fruits and tangerine peel.  Utterly amazing that after five decades plus, a villages level wine can beguile with such pronounced aromatics and still give over the three hours this was drunk.  Light bodied and elegant, with flavors of spice and violets.  Some strawberry notes emerge and linger on a medium plus finish.  Good acidity and a silky mouthfeel that is compelling.  Well stored bottles will still offer pleasure, but this is moving toward the end of it\u2019s plateau of maturity.  Yet another example of a Villages level wine that ages well and offers great drinking.  The 1969 Maison Leroy Vosne Romanee is also worth seeking out, but the '64 has the edge.</p>\n<p>This bottle was from a cold and damp cellar of old Burgundies I bought when I was in France in March.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 11,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-02T23:16:18.069Z",
