      {
        "id": 2191686,
        "name": "Gerhard P.  (P r @ \u20ac s e n t)",
        "username": "Gerhard_P",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/8baadc/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2017-05-31T13:00:14.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"P. Moy\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n P. Moy:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Kris Patten\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Kris Patten:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Leroy didn\u2019t vinify these, correct? These are just negociant bottles that could be from any producer and sold to Leroy as shiners or to be re-labelled</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Correct you are.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Yes, but I do think (Lalou Bize-)Leroy didn\u00b4t buy just \u201cany\u201d wine - but did select very carefully from the very best producers - and selected the very best barrels \u2026 and bottled these eventually. I cannot remember having a \u201cbad\u201d Leroy bottle (except when in bad condition) from the 30ies to the 70ies \u2026 not all were \u201cgreat\u201d but most were excellent \u2026 granted most were/are expensive, and the pricing policy is sometimes ridiculous (e.g. offer of a late release Savigny-les-Beaune Village 1954 (if I\u00b4m correct) in 2014 for something aroung 7000 \u20ac) \u2026 but who buys these must be an idiot or cannot help with too much money \u2026<br>\nFinding such aged bottles (at auction) can be an exciting exercise \u2026 I also doubt that Village-bottles are often fake \u2026 it might be different with Grand crus etc.</p>",
        "post_number": 11,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 11,
